Lecture 09/10

Linear Models, Nests, and Maps

Author

Mike Johnson

Published

February 25, 2025

Last Assignment

  • We created a data.frame documenting the name/abbreviation/region relationship of US states
  • In each case, the column was defined by a character atomic vector

. . .

covid <- read_csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/nytimes/covid-19-data/master/us-counties.csv')

df <- data.frame(region = state.region,
                 abbr = state.abb,
                 state = state.name) 
head(df)
  region abbr      state
1  South   AL    Alabama
2   West   AK     Alaska
3   West   AZ    Arizona
4  South   AR   Arkansas
5   West   CA California
6   West   CO   Colorado

Modeling

What is Modeling?

  • A model is a simplified representation of reality.
  • They helps understand/explain, predict, and analyze complex systems.
  • Common in environmental science, engineering, and many other fields.

Types of Models

Physical Models

  • Scale replicas of real-world systems.
  • Example: A wind tunnel model of an airplane.

Conceptual Models

  • Diagrams or frameworks illustrating relationships.
  • Example: The water cycle.

Mathematical Models

  • Use equations to describe processes.
  • Example: Hydrologic models for streamflow prediction.

Statistical Models

  • Use data and probability to make predictions.
  • Example: Regression models for climate trends.

Why Use Models?

Models …

✅ allow testing scenarios without real-world risks.

✅ provide insights into system behavior.

✅ provide interpretability and easier communication

✅ support improving understanding and making predictions.

✅ are useful for decision-making and policy development.


Limitations of Models

🔴 Simplifications: Models are always approximations, not perfect representations if the critical driving forces aren’t captured, accuracy can be unpredictable.

🔴 Uncertainty: Data quality and assumptions affect accuracy.

🔴 Computational Cost: Some models require high processing power.

Bad Data = Bad Model

🚨 Garbage In, Garbage Out 🚨

🔴 Poor Data Quality Leads to Poor Predictions

  • Incomplete, inaccurate, or biased data skews model outcomes.
  • No amount of complex modeling can fix bad input data.

⚠️️ Common Data Issues:

  • Missing Values → Leads to biased or misleading insights.
  • Incorrect Labels → Misguides supervised learning models.
  • Outliers & Noise → Reduces model reliability.
  • Data Drift → Causes models to become outdated.

✅ Key Takeaway: Better data = Better models. Prioritize data cleaning, validation, and monitoring before training models!

Visualizing Data with visdat in R

What is visdat?

  • visdat is an R package for quick visualizations of data structure and missing values

  • Helps diagnose issues in datasets before analysis

  • Key Functions 🔹 vis_dat(data): Overview of data types

🔹 vis_miss(data): Visualizes missing values

🔹 vis_cor(data): Displays correlations

🔹 vis_guess(data):Shows inferred data types


Why Use visdat?

✅ Quick insights into data

✅ Identifies missing values easily

✅ Helps in preprocessing decisions

Examples

#install.packages("visdat") # Install the package
library(visdat)             # Load the package


vis_dat(penguins)   
vis_miss(penguins)

Data Cleaning

What is data cleaning?

  • The process of detecting, correcting, or removing corrupt, inaccurate, or incomplete data.

  • Ensures data quality, reliability, and usability for analysis.

Why is data cleaning important?

  • Duplicates and missing data can significantly impact the performance and reliability of machine learning and statistical models. Here’s how each issue affects modeling:

Impact of Duplicates

Bias in Model Training:

🔴 If duplicates exist in the training data, the model may overfit to repeated observations, leading to an unrealistic representation of real-world data.

Skewed Distributions:

🔴 Duplicates can artificially inflate the frequency of certain patterns, misleading statistical analyses and causing models to favor duplicated values disproportionately.

Computational Inefficiency:

🔴 Extra, redundant data increases computational load, leading to longer training times and higher memory usage without adding new information.

Overestimation of Model Performance:

🔴 If duplicates exist in both training and test sets, the model might appear to perform better than it actually does because it has seen the exact data points before.

Impact of Missing Data

Bias in Predictions:

🔴 If missing values are not random (e.g., more missing values in a particular category), models trained on incomplete data may develop biased decision rules.

Reduced Model Accuracy:

🔴 Missing values reduce the amount of information available to learn patterns, leading to weaker predictions and generalizations.

Issues with Certain Algorithms:

🔴 Some models, like linear regression and decision trees, can handle missing data through imputation or by ignoring missing values, but others (like most neural networks) require complete data.

Complications in Feature Engineering:

🔴 Many feature transformations, such as standardization and encoding, may not work correctly with missing values, leading to poor feature representation.

Handling Duplicates and Missing Data

Options for Duplicates:

  • Remove exact duplicates when they don’t add information.
  • Analyze near-duplicates to determine if they should be merged, retained, or removed.
df <- df %>% 
  distinct()

For Missing Data:

  • Use imputation techniques (mean, median, mode, regression-based, or KNN imputation). -Remove records if missing data is minimal and its removal won’t introduce bias.
  • Use models that handle missing data natively (e.g., XGBoost can handle missing values).
  • Properly handling duplicates and missing data improves model performance, reliability, and interpretability, ensuring that predictions are more accurate and generalizable.
## Removal
df <- df %>% 
  drop_na()

# Imputation
df <- df %>% 
  mutate(x = mean(x, na.rm = TRUE))

Statistical Models

A. Linear Models (lm) in R

aka Line of Best Fit
aka Ordinary Least Squares (OLS)
aka Linear Regression

Linear Models

  • A Linear Model is a statistical method for modeling relationships between a dependent variable and one or more independent variables.

✅ Commonly used in regression analysis.

✅ Simple and interpretable.

✅ Useful for prediction and understanding relationships in data.

✅ Forms the foundation for more complex models.

Introduction to Linear Models

  • Linear models help us understand relationships between variables.
  • Describe relationships between variables using a mathematical equation that assumes a linear relationship of “best fit”.
  • They take the form: \[ y = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x + \epsilon \]
  • Where:
    • ( y ) is the response variable.
    • ( x ) is the predictor variable.
    • \(\beta_0\) is the intercept (value of ( y ) when ( x = 0 )).
    • \(\beta_1\) is the slope (change in ( y ) for a unit change in ( x )).
    • \(\epsilon\) is the error term.

How do we fine the “Line of Best Fit”?

Method of Ordinary Least Squares (OLS)

Ordinary Least Squares finds the line of best fit for a linear model (in the form of y = mx + b) by minimizing the sum of the residuals squared

where:

residuals are the distance between the sample value (for the dependent variable) and the value predicted by the equation for each value of the independent variable.

Four Main Assumptions for linear regression

  1. Linearity of the relationship between dependent and independent variables
  • Dot

. . .

  1. Independence of the errors (no serial correlation): Error in one measurement (observation) should not influence errors for any other observations

. . .

  1. Homoscedasticty (constant variance) of the errors
    1. versus time
    2. versus the predicted values

. . .

  1. Normality of the residuals

Visualizing Residual spread

Model Explainabilty

How well does our equation describes the relationship between the dependent and independent variable?

  • Coefficient of Determination (R2): the portion of the variance in the dependent variable that is predictable by the independent variable

Ranges from 0 to 1:

  • R2 = 0: The value of the dependent variable cannot be predicted by the value of the independent variable (no correlation)

  • R2 = 1: The value of the dependent variable is perfectly predictable given a value of the independent variable

  • R2 = 0.9: 90% of variance in the dependent variable is predictable from the independent variable

Model Explainabilty

Warning

🚨 Caution when interpreting R2 🚨 - It’s to describe a linear relationship - Higher R2 ≠ better (or more appropriate) model - “Low” R2 doesn’t mean it’s “bad”. R2 values aren’t good or bad. - R2 can be highly influenced by outliers. LOOK AT YOUR DATA!!

The lm() Function in R

Basic Syntax:

model <- lm(y ~ x, data = dataset)

Where:

  • y: Dependent variable (response).

  • ~: Describes a formula as LHS ~ RHS (remember facet_*)

  • x: Independent variable (predictor).

  • dataset: data.frame/tibble containing variables.

Example:

data   <-  penguins |> 
  drop_na()
(model <- lm(flipper_length_mm ~ body_mass_g, data = data))

Call:
lm(formula = flipper_length_mm ~ body_mass_g, data = data)

Coefficients:
(Intercept)  body_mass_g  
   137.0396       0.0152

Data

Intercept

We noted from our model there is a y-intercept of 137.0396

Line of Best Fit

  • From that intercept, the slope of the line is 0.0153 can be mapped
  • This implies that for every increased unit of body mass, flipper length increases by 0.0153 mm

Residuals

Validitiy?

Check quickly for normality and *scedasticity

shapiro.test(data$residuals)

    Shapiro-Wilk normality test

data:  data$residuals
W = 0.95801, p-value = 3.568e-08

    Shapiro-Wilk normality test

data:  data$residuals
W = 0.95801, p-value = 3.568e-08

What is lm

class(model)
[1] "lm"
typeof(model)
[1] "list"
What is s3 class

S3 is a lightweight and flexible object-oriented system in R that allows defining custom classes by assigning a “class” attribute to lists or other base R objects. Methods for S3 classes are dispatched based on the generic function called, using a naming convention like generic.classname(), and R selects the appropriate method based on the object’s class. While S3 lacks formal encapsulation and inheritance mechanisms, it is widely used in R packages due to its simplicity and ease of extension.

✅ Estimate: The estimated coefficient for each predictor.

✅ Std. Error: The standard error of each coefficient.

✅ t value: The test statistic for testing if the coefficient is significantly different from zero.

✅ Pr(>|t|): The p-value for each coefficient.

✅ Significance codes: highly significant, marginally significant, not significant).

Summary Statistics

Residual standard error: 6.847 on 331 degrees of freedom
Multiple R-squared:  0.7621,    Adjusted R-squared:  0.7614 
F-statistic:  1060 on 1 and 331 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

✅ Residual standard error: Measures the average deviation of residuals from the regression line.

✅ Multiple R-squared: Proportion of variance in the dependent variable explained by the model.

✅ Adjusted R-squared: Adjusted for the number of predictors, preventing overfitting.

✅ F-statistic: Tests whether the overall regression model is statistically significant.

✅ A small p-value suggests the model is significant.

Diagnostics

Residuals vs Fitted Plot

plot(model, which = 1)

Purpose:

Checks for non-linearity and homoscedasticity (constant variance of residuals).

Interpretation:

  • Ideally, points should be randomly scattered around the horizontal line at zero.
  • If you see a clear pattern (e.g., a curve), this suggests that your model is missing some non-linearity.
  • If residuals spread out more as fitted values increase, it suggests heteroscedasticity (non-constant variance).

Normal Q-Q Plot

plot(model, which = 2)

Purpose:

Checks if residuals are normally distributed.

Interpretation:

  • If residuals follow a normal distribution, they should fall roughly along the 45-degree reference line.
  • Systematic deviations (e.g., S-shaped curves) indicate non-normality, which might affect inference and prediction intervals.

Scale-Location Plot

plot(model, which = 3)

Purpose:

Checks for homoscedasticity (constant variance of residuals).

Interpretation:

  • This plot shows the square root of the standardized residuals against the fitted values.
  • If the spread (vertical axis) is roughly constant across fitted values, homoscedasticity is satisfied.
  • A fan-like pattern (residuals increasing or decreasing with fitted values) indicates heteroscedasticity.

Cook’s Distance Plot

plot(model, which = 4)

Purpose:

Identifies influential data points that have a large impact on the model.

Interpretation:

  • Cook’s distance measures how much the regression coefficients would change if a particular observation were removed.
  • Points with high Cook’s distance (typically above 0.5 or 1) should be examined, as they may disproportionately affect the model.
  • If a few points stand out, they might be outliers or high-leverage points, and you should investigate whether they are errors or legitimate influential points.

Residuals vs Leverage Plot

plot(model, which = 5)

Purpose:

Identifies influential observations that might disproportionately affect the model.

Interpretation:

  • Leverage measures how extreme a point’s predictor values are.
  • Residuals measure how far a point’s response value is from the fitted line.
  • The red dashed line represents Cook’s distance; points beyond this line might be influential.
  • If a point has both high leverage and large residuals, it might unduly influence the regression and should be investigated.

Making predictions using lm()

predict is a generic function for predictions from the results of various model fitting functions. The function invokes particular methods which depend on the class of the first argument.

(new_data <- summarise(data, body_mass_g = mean(body_mass_g)))
# A tibble: 1 × 1
  body_mass_g
        <dbl>
1       4207.

. . .

predict(model, new_data)
      1 
200.967

Across a population

df = data.frame(penguin_id = 1:100) |> 
  mutate(body_mass_g = abs(rnorm(n(), 
                           mean(data$body_mass_g), 
                           sd(data$body_mass_g)))) %>%
  mutate(flipper_length_mm = predict(model, .))

Remember the difference in pipes described in lab 2?

Tidyverse Pipe (%>%)

From the magrittr package (and used in dplyr), %>% allows greater flexibility than |>, such as:

  • Using placeholders (.) when the first argument isn’t where the function expects input.
  • Automatically handling non-standard evaluation in dplyr.

Option 2: broom

  • The broom package helps tidy up model outputs for further analysis or reporting.
  • It converts model objects (like from lm()) into tidy data.frames that are easy to manipulate.
"broom" %in% tidyverse_packages()
[1] TRUE

Key functions from broom include:

  • tidy() for converting model coefficients and statistics into a data frame.
  • glance() for providing a one-row summary of a model’s performance.
  • augment() for adding model diagnostics (e.g., residuals, fitted values) to the original data.
library(broom)

Vectors in R

  • Two types: atomic (same type) and lists (mixed types).
  • NULL is a zero-length vector.
df = data.frame(x = 1:10, y = letters[1:10])
df$list_element = vector("list", length = nrow(df))
head(df)
  x y list_element
1 1 a         NULL
2 2 b         NULL
3 3 c         NULL
4 4 d         NULL
5 5 e         NULL
6 6 f         NULL

Lists

  • Atomic vectors store base types (logical, character, numeric).
  • Lists can store anything (including other lists!).
models = list(
  lm(flipper_length_mm ~ body_mass_g, data = data),
  lm(flipper_length_mm ~ bill_length_mm, data = data),
  lm(flipper_length_mm ~ bill_depth_mm, data = data)
)

Data Frames & Lists

  • data.frames = structured lists of atomic vectors.
  • Can’t store lists as columns.

Introduction to purrr

✅ Verbs like mutate work well across columns, but cannot work over nested lists (e.g. a list-column of a tibble (list!))

✅ purrr is an R package designed to enhance iteration, functional programming, and list manipulation. It provides a cohesive and readable alternative to base R functions like lapply(), sapply(), and apply(). The core philosophy of purrr is to make function application more predictable and consistent.

✅ Much like dplyr /groups work together, purrr/nests operate harmoniously

"purrr" %in% tidyverse_packages()
[1] TRUE

Core Functions in purrr

1. map()

  • The map() function applies a function to each element of a list or vector and returns a list.
  • It works similarly to lapply() but with better integration into tidyverse workflows.
numbers <- list(1, 2, 3, 4, 5)
map(numbers, ~ .x^2)
[[1]]
[1] 1

[[2]]
[1] 4

[[3]]
[1] 9

[[4]]
[1] 16

[[5]]
[1] 25

Explanation:

  • The .x notation inside map() refers to the data frame being operated on.

2. map_*() Variants

  • map() → Returns a list
  • map_lgl() → Returns a logical vector
  • map_int() → Returns an integer vector
  • map_dbl() → Returns a double (numeric) vector
  • map_chr() → Returns a character vector

Example:

numbers <- list(1, 2, 3, 4, 5)
map_dbl(numbers, ~ .x^2)
[1]  1  4  9 16 25

3. map2()

map2() applies a function to two lists element-wise.

Example:

list1 <- list(1, 2, 3)
list2 <- list(4, 5, 6)
map2(list1, list2, ~ .x + .y)
[[1]]
[1] 5

[[2]]
[1] 7

[[3]]
[1] 9

4. pmap()

pmap() extends map2() to handle multiple lists.

Example:

a <- list(1, 2, 3)
b <- list(4, 5, 6)
c <- list(7, 8, 9)
pmap(list(a = a, b = b, c = c), function(a,b,c) a + b + c)
[[1]]
[1] 12

[[2]]
[1] 15

[[3]]
[1] 18

Unnesting

nested_data |> 
  mutate(mean_flipper = map(data, ~mean(.x$flipper_length_mm))) |> 
  unnest(mean_flipper)
# A tibble: 3 × 3

1 Adelie    <tibble [152 × 7]>          NA 
2 Gentoo    <tibble [124 × 7]>          NA 
3 Chinstrap <tibble [68 × 7]>          196.

Combining nest() and map()

  • nest() structures the data into list-column objects
  • map() applies functions over list objects to each nested dataset.
  • model objects are S3 list objects with methods that can be applied
  • Can be used for modeling, summaries, and transformations.

Example: Linear Regression by Group

   drop_na() |> 
   nest(data = -species))

Explanation:

  • glance() accepts a model object and returns a tibble() with exactly one row of model summaries. The summaries are typically goodness of fit measures, p-values for hypothesis tests on residuals, or model convergence information.

Extracting Model Summaries with broom

nested_data |> 
  mutate(model   = map(data, ~lm(flipper_length_mm ~ body_mass_g, data = .x)),
         summary = map2(model, data, ~broom::augment(.x, newdata = .y))) |> 
  unnest(summary)
# A tibble: 333 × 12
   species data     model  island bill_length_mm bill_depth_mm flipper_length_mm
   <fct>   <list>   <list> <fct>           <dbl>         <dbl>             <int>
 1 Adelie  <tibble> <lm>   Torge…           39.1          18.7               181
 2 Adelie  <tibble> <lm>   Torge…           39.5          17.4               186
 3 Adelie  <tibble> <lm>   Torge…           40.3          18                 195
 4 Adelie  <tibble> <lm>   Torge…           36.7          19.3               193
 5 Adelie  <tibble> <lm>   Torge…           39.3          20.6               190
 6 Adelie  <tibble> <lm>   Torge…           38.9          17.8               181
 7 Adelie  <tibble> <lm>   Torge…           39.2          19.6               195
 8 Adelie  <tibble> <lm>   Torge…           41.1          17.6               182
 9 Adelie  <tibble> <lm>   Torge…           38.6          21.2               191
10 Adelie  <tibble> <lm>   Torge…           34.6          21.1               198
# ℹ 323 more rows
# ℹ 5 more variables: body_mass_g <int>, sex <fct>, year <int>, .fitted <dbl>,
#   .resid <dbl>

Explanation:

  • augment accepts a model object and a dataset and adds information about each observation in the dataset. Most commonly, this includes predicted values in the .fitted column, residuals in the .resid column, and standard errors for the fitted values in a .se.fit column. New columns always begin with a . prefix to avoid overwriting columns in the original dataset.
  • Since augment requires the dataset and model, map2 is needed!!!

Summary

  • visdat is a useful library for

    • visualizing data structure
    • identifying missing values
    • checking correlations
    • inferring data types

  • lm() is a powerful function for linear regression in R.

    • Returns an s3 object of class lm

  • summary() provides key insights about lm models

  • predict() can be make predictions for new data

  • tibble is a tidyverse data frame that supports list-columns and other operations/print methods

  • broom provides a way to tidy up model outputs for easier interpretation and reporting.

  • nest() is useful for grouping and restructuring data.

  • map*() enables functional programming and efficient iteration.

Linear Models as the Basis for Machine Learning

Why is lm() Fundamental to ML?

Linear regression is the simplest form of a predictive model and forms the basis of many ML algorithms, such as:

1. Logistic Regression (for classification)

  • Example: Predicting water contamination based on pH, turbidity, and dissolved oxygen.

2. Support Vector Machines (Linear Kernel)

  • Example: Classifying land cover types (urban vs. vegetation) using remote sensing data.

3. Neural Networks (Linear Combinations in Layers)

  • Example: Modeling soil moisture dynamics with meteorological variables.

OLS-Based ML Methods in Environmental Science

4. Generalized Linear Models (GLMs)

  • Example: Predicting species distribution based on climate variables (temperature, precipitation).

5. Regularization: Ridge & Lasso Regression

  • Example: Predicting air pollution levels (PM2.5) while selecting the most important features.

6. Partial Least Squares Regression (PLSR)

  • Useful for high-dimensional data (e.g., hyperspectral satellite imagery).
  • Example: Predicting chlorophyll-a concentration in lakes.

OLS-Based ML Methods in Environmental Science

7. Principal Component Regression (PCR)

  • Reduces collinearity using PCA before regression.
  • Example: Identifying key meteorological drivers of air quality changes.

8. Generalized Additive Models (GAMs)

  • Allows nonlinear relationships using splines.
  • Example: Modeling temperature impacts on species migration.

9. Mixed-Effects Models (LMMs/GLMMs)

  • Handles spatial and hierarchical dependencies.
  • Example: Estimating streamflow changes across watersheds.

OLS-Based ML Methods in Environmental Science

10. Elastic Net Regression

  • Combines Ridge & Lasso for variable selection and shrinkage.
  • Example: Modeling urban heat island effects.

11. Bayesian Regression

  • Incorporates prior knowledge and uncertainty.
  • Example: Predicting future drought probabilities based on historical trends.

12. Deep Learning & Matrix Multiplication

  • Many deep learning models extend OLS concepts through matrix operations.
  • Example: Using CNNs for forest fire detection in satellite imagery.

Today’s Assignment

Using the airquality from R datasets

  1. Use the help (?) function to learn more about the dataset

  2. Use vis_dat to check out the data. Does it need cleaning?

  3. Fit a linear model to the cleaned data to predict Ozone from one of the possible predictors of your choosing. Why did you chose that variable?

  4. Using summary(), Does this seem like a valid model?

  5. Explain the R2 found in a sentence.

  6. Use broom::augment to predict the Ozone of the cleaned data

  7. Use ggplot to plot the actual vs predicted Ozone

    • Add a red line to show where the actual and predicted values are equal
      • This can be done by plotting a 1:1 line (e.g. intercept 0, slope 1) with geom_abline(intercept = 0, slope = 1, color = "red")
    • Add a subtitle to the plot showing the correlation between the actual and predicted values are equal
      • This can be done with paste("Correlation:", round(cor(a$Ozone, a$.fitted),2)) assuming your augmented data object is called a
